*)Ansible is a configuration management and automation tool used to manage and configure many servers from one place or one server.

*)Ansible is an agentless tool(No software installation needed on remote servers), which means it performs automation 
  without installing any agent or additional software in managed nodes(remote servers). It uses SSH (Secure Shell) protocol to communicate with remote servers.

*)A control node is the main machine where Ansible is installed, managed nodes are the servers managed by the control node.
  
*)Ansible playbooks are written in YAML format. We use YAML in Ansible because it is simple, human-readable, and easy to write.
  Ansible playbooks are written in YAML format to define automation tasks in a structured way.
  
#)Indentation: 

*)Indentation is important in YAML because YAML uses spaces to define structure and hierarchy. Incorrect indentation can cause syntax errors and playbook failures.

*)Playbook: A playbook is a collection of one or more plays that contains tasks.

#)YAML:

*)YAML is a simple and human-readable language used to write Ansible playbooks in a structured format.

#)SSH:

*)SSH stands for Secure Shell. It is a secure protocol used to connect and communicate with servers remotely over a network.

Playbook → Collection of plays
Play → Defines target hosts and tasks
Task → Single action that will be performed on the managed nodes or remote servers by Ansible.
Module → Performs the actual work


Explanation of Playbook with an example:
----------------------------------------

- name: Configure web servers
  hosts: webservers
  tasks:
    - name: Install nginx
      apt:
        name: nginx
        state: present

- name: Configure database servers
  hosts: dbservers
  tasks:
    - name: Install mysql
      apt:
        name: mysql-server
        state: present
	
	
*)Entire file → One PLAYBOOK
  First - name block → First PLAY
  Second - name block → Second PLAY


*)Same hosts/groups unte → same play + multiple tasks. i.e. If the same host group is used, multiple tasks can be written in the same play.

*)Different hosts/groups unte → multiple plays better practice🌿 i.e. If different host groups are used, using multiple plays is a better practice.

*)A playbook starts with -(hyphen) to define a play and "name:" is optional and used to describe the play or task for human readable format.

*)hosts: defines the target server where the tasks are executed.

*)Each task starts with -(hyphen) and task has a name and a module, Modules perform the actual action. 


1)Without Ansible:

*)You must login to each server
*)Run commands one by one
*)High chance of mistakes
*)Wastes time

2)With Ansible:

*)Write instructions once
*)Run them on all servers at the same time
*)Same configuration everywhere
*)Faster and error-free


